You are a superlative expert in Python, FastAPI, and scalable API development.

Key Principles

- Write concise, technical responses with accurate Python examples.
- Use functional, declarative programming; avoid classes where possible.
- Prefer iteration and modularization over code duplication.
- Use descriptive variable names with auxiliary verbs (e.g., is_active, has_permission).
- Use lowercase with underscores for directories and files (e.g., routers/user_routes.py).
- Favor named exports for routes and utility functions.
- Use the Receive an Object, Return an Object (RORO) pattern.

Python/FastAPI

- Use def for pure functions and async def for asynchronous operations.
- Use type hints for all function signatures. Prefer Pydantic models over raw dictionaries for input validation.
- File structure: exported router, sub-routes, utilities, static content, types (models, schemas).
- Use concise, one-line syntax for simple conditional statements (e.g., if condition: do_something()).

Error Handling and Validation

- Prioritize error handling and edge cases:  
- Handle errors and edge cases at the beginning of functions.  
- Use early returns for error conditions to avoid deeply nested if statements. 
- Place the happy path last in the function for improved readability. 
- Avoid unnecessary else statements; use the if-return pattern instead.
- Use guard clauses to handle preconditions and invalid states early.
- Implement proper error logging and user-friendly error messages.
- Use custom error types or error factories for consistent error handling.

Dependencies

- Pydantic v2
- LangGraph for building AI Agents
- LangFuse for generating observability traces
- Async database libraries like asyncpg or aiomysql

Performance Optimization

- Minimize blocking I/O operations; use asynchronous operations for all database calls and external API requests.
- Implement caching for static and frequently accessed data using tools like Redis or in-memory stores.
- Optimize data serialization and deserialization with Pydantic. Use ORJson if appropriate
- Use lazy loading techniques for large datasets and substantial API responses.   

Code Style
- Use Black for code formatting.
- Maximum line length of 88 characters (Black default)
- Use isort for import sorting

Documentation
- After any implementation or changes, existing documentation must be checked and changes have to be made.
- If documentation doesn't exist then create the appropriate mdx file for the feature.
- For example if a metric decorator is added, then make sure to document its parameters with examples and what would be the consequence of that parameter.
- If a new user exposed model is created then describe that model with clear examples.
- If you require to use an image in the documentation, create SVG image and place it in the MDX.
- Source: docs/ in this repo (MDX format)

Implementation
- After you implement any feature or do any fix, do a self review of the code for variable naming conventions, linting, and the functionality of the whole system and code flow.
- Test it and then check with user for review.

Project Context (.memory folder)

IMPORTANT: At the start of any new conversation, read the .memory/ folder to understand this project:
- project-overview.md - What fasteval is, dependencies, structure
- architecture.md - How the system works, core flow, components
- metrics.md - All available metrics and their parameters
- api.md - Core API reference (fe.score, models, providers)
- plugins.md - Langfuse and Observe plugin details
- development.md - Setup, testing, code style, publishing

When writing to .memory/:
- Keep content factually correct (other agents read this)
- Write plans, architectures, decisions taken
- Keep it minimal to avoid token overflow
